</head>
<body>

  <h1>Forms with change history</h1>

  <h2>Rationale</h2>

  <p>Immediately after a form gets implemented, it enters the
  "maintenance" phase: every once-in-a-while, the form needs to get
  updated.  Adding fields, removing fields, changing fields.  In common
  practice, the users of the form is not informed about those changes.
  However, that may not be the optimal experience, both from the form
  owner and from the form user's perspective.</p>

  <p>A few examples where it would really help to display the changes
  since the last visit of the user:</p>
  <ul>
  <li>the user gets a new option to indicate whether the phone number is for home or work,
  <li>the accepted length of the company description has been enlarged,
  <li>the license has to be reconfirmed,
  <li>a new gender option was added which may fit you better, or
  <li>the postal address became optional: you are allowed to remove it.
  </ul>

  <p>Over time, small changes to the form are made.  How do you
  communicate them clearly to a user?  This based on the knowledge: when
  did the user visit the form last?</p>

  <h3>Compatibility</h3>

  <p>This page demonstrates the features of this module, tested with
  Bootstrap 5.3.8 and jQuery 3.7.1.  Very probably, this doe will also
  work with older or newer releases of Bootstrap and Bootstrap: please
  report your successes.</p>

  <h3>Future developments</h3>

  <ul>
  <li>integration with the validation component.</li>
  <li>porting the features to other web frameworks.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Concepts</h2>

  <p>The form change record is added to the HTML in divs.  What has changed
  and when is encoded in class attributes and data attributes.  When the form
  is loaded, it is informed about the version of the form when the user clicked
  "Save" last.  All the form changes since that moment will get visualized.</p>

  <h3>Form and data version</h3>

  <p>To be able to see the changes, you need to track the version of the form
  which the user filled-in.  This is not the version of the form on the moment
  the user submits, but the version the user saw in the browser.  Typically, your
  form starts like this:</p>

#fragment/form-version.html.code

  <p>The version <strong>MUST be strictly alphabetically ordered</strong>.  A date
  with or without time will do.  Versions like '<tt>2.8.12</tt>' will <em>not</em>
  work.</p>

  <p>When the server accepts the form data, it shall implement something like:

#fragment/backend-accept.perl.code

  <p>Translate this to your own server language and web-framework.  (I will include
  your solutions as examples, if you contribute them.)</p>

  <h3>Starting the "changes" plugin</h3>

  <p>Besides the two extra hidden fields in your form, you also need to start the
  jQuery plugin.  Add this to your HTML:</p>

#fragment/bs5/load.html.code

  <p>When you attach the <tt>changes</tt> plugin to your form, you can pass
  a configuration.  You may use different configurations for different forms
  on your page.  Currently, the only support option is <tt>style</tt>.</p>

  <h3>Display styles</h3>

  <p>Based on the same basic change specification, you can select different
  visualization styles.  Specify the <tt>style</tt> at configuration, which
  overrules the <tt>data-change-style</tt> attribute on the <tt>form</tt>.</p>

  <p>Style <tt>pill</tt> (the default) is a pretty heavy display of
  the change information.  The only other option (at the moment) is
  style <tt>dot</tt>, which attempts to be helpful with less visual
  load.  The examples below demonstrate the differences.</p>

  <h3>Change history template</h3>

  <p>Form change information can be added to every kind of form field, and
  as special change notes.  First a generic example:</p>

#fragment/bs5/global.html.code

  <p>Above HTML example shows a typical Bootstrap text input field.
  The <tt>&lt;div&gt;</tt> blocks tagged '<tt>change</tt>' and
  '<tt>change-note</tt>' are the additions handled by this plugin.</p>

  <p>When the user's data is older than '<tt>changed-in</tt>'
  (here version 20251010), then the change will be made visual to the user
  of the form.  Not shown here is the '<tt>change-hide</tt>' attribute,
  which is used when a new change block eclipses an older version.
  Some styles may use the '<tt>summary</tt>' for immediate display.
  The content of the <tt>&lt;div&gt;</tt> MAY be displayed on demand.</p>

  <p>As you could have guessed from the '<tt>for</tt>' attribute: you MAY put the
  change describing block somewhere else in the HTML file: as long as it is part
  of the same <tt>form</tt> structure.</p>

  <h2>Visualizations</h2>

  <p>Based on the applicable change blocks, visualizations are produced.  The
  block either describes a note, or a form field.</p>

  <h3>Change notes</h3>

  <p>HTML blocks (usually <tt>fieldset</tt> blocks) which are marked
  with class '<tt>change-note</tt>' are shown when the user's data
  version is older than '<tt>data-changed-in</tt>' and not older than
  '<tt>data-change-hide</tt>'.</p>

  <p>When you use a <tt>fieldset</tt> block, then the additional class
  '<tt>framed</tt>' can be used for a nice decoration.  In that case,
  class '<tt>dismissable</tt>' can be added to get a <em>close</em>
  symbol to click away the note.</p>

